{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 12:29:00.346831", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Clos EBGP Lab\nDate: (current capture)\n\nSummary\n- The multi-tier Clos (fat‑tree) topology is functionally healthy based on the collected data. Host-to-host connectivity tests succeeded, BGP sessions are established, and all expected /24 host subnets are present in the routing tables across routers.\n- No data-plane reachability failures or missing route advertisements were observed for the hosts and prefixes in the provided topology (pc_0_0, pc_0_1 and the learned 10.0.x/24 — 10.3.x/24 ranges).\n\nSources of evidence used\n- Full reachability sweep between hosts (ping results).\n- FRR running configuration and IPv4 routing table snapshots from:\n  - super_spine_router_0\n  - spine_router_0_0\n  - spine_router_0_1\n  - leaf_router_0_0\n  - leaf_router_0_1\n\nKey findings (detailed)\n\n1) Data-plane reachability (hosts)\n- Pings between hosts succeeded with 0% loss in sampled tests. Representative tests show RTTs in low milliseconds (typical range approx 1–7 ms across the fabric).\n- Conclusion: Host-level connectivity is functional and no packet loss was detected in the sampled tests.\n\n2) Control-plane (BGP) — session presence and route propagation\n- All routers show BGP-learned routes for the expected 10.<pod>.<leaf>.0/24 host subnets.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 advertises network 10.0.0.0/24 (C>* present).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 advertises network 10.0.1.0/24 (C>* present).\n- Spine and super‑spine routing tables contain entries for the full set of /24s (10.0.0.0/24 through 10.3.7.0/24) and have clear BGP next-hops toward the spines/leaves.\n  - Example: super_spine_router_0 shows B>* 10.0.0.0/24 … via 172.16.0.3, eth1 (BGP learned).\n  - Spines show multipath-like learned entries for many prefixes (multiple next-hops listed), consistent with a Clos topology where multiple spines connect to leaves and super‑spines.\n- No missing /24 prefixes were observed in any of the provided routing tables.\n\n3) Interface/connectivity state (inter-router links)\n- The connected (C) routes for the /31 inter-router links are present on all examined routers (e.g., super_spine_router_0 lists many 172.16.0.x/31 addresses as directly connected).\n- This confirms the underlay links are up from the perspective of the routers whose routing tables were captured.\n\nNon-critical or noteworthy observations (possible operational concerns, not service failures)\n- super_spine_router_0 router-id is configured as 172.16.0.0. That address is typically a network address in some schemata and using .0 as the router-id is unusual (but not inherently fatal). It could be an artifact of templated configuration or testbed addressing. This is informational only.\n- FRR debugging lines present in each router configuration: \"debug bgp keepalives\", \"debug bgp updates in\", \"debug bgp updates out\" are enabled in the configurations. While this does not indicate a current failure, debug-level logging can be noisy and may affect CPU/logging behavior on busy devices — an operational note rather than a functional fault seen in these captures.\n\nAnomalies / Faults\n- No control-plane anomalies identified: BGP sessions appear established and routes are propagated across layers.\n- No data-plane anomalies identified: host pings succeeded with no loss; routing tables include expected prefixes and correct next-hops.\n- Therefore, no faulty device or failing link was localized from the captured outputs.\n\nLocalization & root-cause analysis\n- Localization: N/A — no failing device, session, or link found to localize.\n- Root cause: N/A — since no outage or degradation was detected, there is no root cause to identify from the provided captures.\n\nState summary (short)\n- BGP: Established and advertising/learning expected prefixes across super-spine, spine, and leaf routers.\n- Underlay: Inter-router /31 links appear up (connected routes present).\n- Hosts: Reachable to other end-hosts in the sample (0% ping loss).\n- No missing routes or forwarding blackholes observed in the sampled view.\n\nIf further diagnostics are desired (not requested in this report), useful next steps would be to collect BGP neighbor summary/state, bgp table sizes, interface counters (errors, drops), and FRR logs to look for transient flapping or policy issues. (No mitigation or configuration changes are proposed in this report per instructions.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 23863, "output_tokens": 2175, "total_tokens": 26038, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8832}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1152}}}
